uild target supports JUnit 5 since there's currently no public class; we'll need to make one. \\n\\nI also want to cover the private `findWin` method by simulating a Windows OS and using `Runtime.exec(\\\"ipconfig /all\\\")`. However, will it recognize `ipconfig`? It seems the testing environment might complicate matters with the system path. If the OS isn't set correctly, like on Linux, there could be issues with the process. I need to consider carefully how to approach this without missing key elements.\\n\\n**Exploring testing options**\\n\\nI can't use direct reflection, so maybe I could employ a public refresh method with `os.name` set to Windows alongside some module tricks. Unfortunately, I can't intercept `ipconfig` directly. The `findWin(InputStream)` method is private, which complicates things, and upstream tests might be trying to use reflection, which isn't allowed.\\n\\nHowever, I think I can trigger `findWin` via the constructor and simulate a `Runtime.exec` command. I need to ensure that `findSunJVM` returns false as well. It seems that `Class.forName(\\\"sun.net.dns.ResolverConfiguration\\\")` might not be supported, but maybe it will be included in the metadata. Yet, the JVM dynamic report suggests this isn't covered; perhaps the constructor didn’t execute `findSunJVM`. \\n\\nIt's puzzling that the existing placeholder doesn’t interact with `ResolverConfig`. If I instantiate `ResolverConfig` without DNS properties, it should call `findSunJVM`, which is good. With JDK 21, I wonder if the class exists. If `Class.forName` fails, I might need to check the remaining coverage with `getMethod`. I think I could cover six sites for `findSunJVM` simply by creating a new `ResolverConfig`. However, if nameservers are empty, will the invocation still be covered?\\n\\n**Analyzing resource bundle conditions**\\n\\nFor the `findWin` resource bundle, I need to invoke `findNT` or `find95`. It seems important for `findSunJVM` to fail or for the servers and search list to be unset. The constructor will only proceed with the OS check if `servers` or `searchlist` is null. If `findSunJVM` returns true, then `servers` will be non-null, but I wonder if the search list can still be empty. This setup could impact how I handle server configurations.\\n\\n**Exploring resource bundles**\\n\\nI'm trying to figure out the issue with Windows and resource bundles. Skipping Windows seems like it wouldn't work well, as it could trigger `ResourceBundle.getBundle` in `findWin` through the public API. I wonder if the `SimpleResolver` or `Lookup` has properties that I can search for to help with this. There's definitely something here worth investigating further! I want to ensure I find the best solution.\", \"thinkingSignature\": \"{\\\"id\\\":\\\"rs_0ee368ff6ff029c80169f4daf1a9cc819cba005a0f496d2396\\\",\\\"type\\\":\\\"reasoning\\\",\\\"encrypted_content\\\":\\\"gAAAAABp9NsJGonYyacQV3UBBVtbrbaTyg3cEsAy1uQcfq7Bb4Q19EP8uta-uWxh6h3QJS2RJkxnLzY39xKUUELoMEYnA_5RghPBjuhkPna1nylzD2z888f2EIy6XzMrBobN7u1PiyMhTZKwd6AIU1M7BD3NUbb9GeorQVjvy5NQUfCrNqgHhkS4i3GbQPeDoh-_7La5EoTl7XFPTQc57pOZLg4EafQ3FCDjVAgjmi4Dtz8FumDVg28WNumySHbbssa3YJnQSVL9C5x3hyP0Gh1BRHShUPVGds2atFtmw6B3aWeVjD6AVEG7PWqyAIwHXFbXmHfXLzAEq9-EitZ8CepP2VEYVCoYwqczdxMvlzYeaWFz5S7m3iA8ilbnkdG1OgWjTB9UjXZsIj24-96qKn7-R6E2schuQ_yqkSiGoWEm2M_kq2soMAvdUHlkRr2P3SZdePOAPHnE3HgmRfw7gR1QQR8MbYIThUvdao3-XZ8Ofye6r0M4o9TB0ro9Sh1wpRB6NJZohB88Tjl2E0IIBwCIKhsSTTd1cqC84UWQ8JM36HpkMvHNHvWwJWMUKezMS19SQQ_iRTCiOmVIrLtWjBLFCA80k6JG0__HUE1RS8jLroEZ8SXBhL324qlmV5S0sKBQMDVtSwAM7H2ZEk_d28XMH4ArXHwtG5nzFDrbEJ_7dQwPtF6fEAmWPxi1UH7iVD6z77ohDwDlfTEhJXup3BPu6hZq7PLOoVmQhl5vpumXKLGbYFRhdS-PxElSv8vN18xSjIqpHuWCaMEpED-i66SzlY2ZPW1yZq_Z3GsiShgR9NlOzGO01YZYiqP5NznDDFvXrDDL6atCWuo4iGcQZC4IHJw3Oeoto0x6XMx1NwTzXHTrhfFX0mhDbxBukXjrMPR5t1b65QnbNdprF_Z0gAscIA1ALJFkmJsvuYf-i8Yn0t24leABm9sOac7xJqzJERFbONFeBJ3qN32gFpSoj54xtpOXOfkEexwNEDjjAMFvqHzu_PXGUEEIO3qw8ig-sI_4ZdQLFSxtnwFYTuYfwOP9k6E0LhvRpQ8lO7ITXY9DojhbN9lskiUHc7_WUaUasLColAtWUeeYAr96Y